SATIRE X.

The subject of this Satire is the Vanity of Human WVishes. The poet takes his stand on the great theatre of the world and summons before him the illustrious characters of 311 ages. As they appear in succession, he shows, from the principal events “ of their lives, how little happiness is promoted, by the attainment of what our indis-tinet and bounded views represent, as the most perfect of earthly blessings. Of these he instances walth, power, eloquence, military glory, and persona] accomplishments3 all which have, as he observes, proved dangerous or destructive to their respective possessors. From hence, he argues the wis- dom of acquiescing in the dispensations of Heaven; und con- cludes with a form of prayer, in which he points out, with great force and beauty, the objects for which a rational being may pre— sume to approach the Almighty.

Juvenal seems, in the composition of this satire, to have had in his thoughts Plato’s second dialogue of Alcibiades and Per- sius's second Satire ; he has, however, taken nothing from them, but the general idea 3 the filling up is entirely his own.
